1777333031474478	bones-dev	itc:v3:AWKSZJkkk5JkmZMxAAAAQatWqrq1bWwAAAE35Aw		item.create	bn-70q8	{"description":"File: crates/bones-core/src/cache/manager.rs, crates/bones-core/src/cache/writer.rs, crates/bones-cli/src/cmd/rebuild.rs\n\nIssue:\n`CacheManager` treats the binary cache header's `created_at_us` field as the shard-directory fingerprint, but the public rebuild path writes wall-clock time into that same field. A cache produced by `CacheManager::rebuild()` or `bn admin rebuild` therefore fails `CacheManager::is_fresh()` immediately and the next `CacheManager::load_events()` falls back to TSJSON and rebuilds again.\n\nRoot Cause:\n`CacheManager::is_fresh()` and `load_events()` compare `CacheReader::created_at_us()` to `fingerprint_dir(...)` (`manager.rs:102-132`). The manager's fallback path uses `rebuild_with_fingerprint(...)` and stores the fingerprint in the header (`manager.rs:220-238`). But `CacheManager::rebuild()` delegates to `rebuild_cache(...)` (`manager.rs:175-177`), and `bn admin rebuild` also calls `bones_core::cache::rebuild_cache(...)` (`cmd/rebuild.rs:70`). `rebuild_cache(...)` uses `CacheWriter::write_to_file(...)`, which sets `created_at_us = now_us()` (`writer.rs:50-60`).\n\nImpact:\nThe public/manual cache rebuild output is logically stale as soon as it is written for any caller using `CacheManager` freshness semantics. This defeats the binary cache fast path after `bn admin rebuild`, causes unnecessary TSJSON parsing and cache rewrites, and leaves two incompatible interpretations of the same cache header field in the public API.\n\nEvidence:\n- `manager.rs:16-17` documents that `created_at_us` is repurposed to store the fingerprint.\n- `manager.rs:107-109` and `manager.rs:131-132` compare `reader.created_at_us()` to the current fingerprint.\n- `manager.rs:175-177` exposes a public rebuild method that does not use `rebuild_with_fingerprint`.\n- `writer.rs:56-58` stores wall-clock microseconds instead of a fingerprint.\n- `cmd/rebuild.rs:70` writes the same wall-clock cache during `bn admin rebuild`.\n\nSuggested fix:\nUnify cache creation semantics. Either make `rebuild_cache` accept/store the fingerprint used by `CacheManager`, or stop overloading `created_at_us` and add explicit cache metadata for the source fingerprint. Add a regression test that calls `CacheManager::rebuild()` (and ideally the admin rebuild path) then verifies `is_fresh()` is true and `load_events()` returns `LoadSource::Cache`.\n\nRelated:\nFound during the second fresh-eyes pass after fixing bn-250m, bn-296y, and bn-3jzf.","kind":"bug","labels":["fresh-eyes","cache","correctness"],"size":"s","title":"Public cache rebuild writes stale freshness metadata"}	blake3:XLfLJ10Gfpy37d6eVtxNx21T5N8STK2qCaeu2kXbtqo
1777333045195874	bones-dev	itc:v3:AWKSZJkkk5JkmZMxAAAAQatWqrq1bWwAAAE35Qw		item.create	bn-1dj8	{"description":"File: crates/bones-triage/src/graph/build.rs, crates/bones-cli/src/cmd/triage_support.rs\n\nIssue:\nThe triage PageRank cache is keyed by a graph content hash that includes only blocking edges, not the active node set. Adding or removing active items without changing dependency edges leaves `RawGraph::content_hash` unchanged, so `compute_pagerank` can return cached scores from the old graph instead of recomputing for the new node count.\n\nRoot Cause:\n`RawGraph::from_sqlite` loads all non-deleted items as graph nodes (`build.rs:81-90`) but computes `content_hash` only from `load_blocking_edges(...)` (`build.rs:92-97`). `compute_edge_hash` hashes only `(blocker, blocked)` pairs (`build.rs:196-205`). `compute_pagerank` treats `cache.content_hash == normalized.content_hash()` as a complete cache hit and returns cached scores directly (`triage_support.rs:385-397`).\n\nImpact:\nTriage scoring can use stale PageRank after item-only changes. New active items with no dependencies receive `pr_raw = 0.0` because their IDs are absent from the cached score map (`triage_support.rs:151-154`), while a full PageRank recompute would include them in the graph and assign the uniform/dangling baseline. Removed items can also leave the cache shape inconsistent until an edge changes. This biases `bn triage`/`bn next` recommendations after ordinary create/delete operations that do not touch dependencies.\n\nEvidence:\n- `build.rs:68-73` says all non-deleted items are graph nodes, but the content hash changes only when edges change.\n- `triage_support.rs:386-397` returns cached scores without checking node count, node IDs, cache version, or score coverage.\n- `triage_support.rs:151-154` maps active item IDs through `pagerank_result.scores` and defaults missing IDs to zero.\n\nSuggested fix:\nInclude the sorted active node IDs and cache schema/version in the graph/cache fingerprint, or validate that the cached score map exactly covers the current active node set before accepting a hit. Add a regression test that builds a PageRank cache, adds an unblocked active item with no dependency edges, runs triage again, and asserts the cache is invalidated or the new item has the same PageRank baseline as a full recompute.\n\nRelated:\nFound during the second fresh-eyes pass. Nearby prior work: bn-bdcfd1d68 introduced incremental DF-PageRank cache integration.","kind":"bug","labels":["fresh-eyes","triage","cache","correctness"],"size":"m","title":"Triage PageRank cache ignores item-only graph changes"}	blake3:_lWhg0tkxoPJGvCxfiETQLAR-ymRef1b5Vf-BMGnoto
1777333059880968	bones-dev	itc:v3:AWKSZJkkk5JkmZMxAAAAQatWqrq1bWwAAAE35gw		item.create	bn-1nk1	{"description":"File: crates/bones-core/src/db/mod.rs, crates/bones-core/src/db/incremental.rs, crates/bones-cli/src/cmd/doctor.rs, crates/bones-cli/src/cmd/diagnose.rs\n\nIssue:\nNormal projection opening only compares the stored cursor byte offset to the total event-log byte length. If the event log changes without changing total byte length, or if the projection cursor hash no longer matches the current last event hash, `ensure_projection` returns the existing SQLite projection without rebuilding. `bn doctor` has the same offset-only blind spot, while `bn diagnose` already computes and reports the hash mismatch.\n\nRoot Cause:\n`ensure_projection` decides freshness from `total_bytes != cursor` after reading `projection_meta.last_event_offset` (`db/mod.rs:77-93`). It ignores `projection_meta.last_event_hash` whenever the byte offset is non-zero. The stronger cursor-hash validation in `incremental_apply` (`incremental.rs:140-152`) only runs after `ensure_projection` has already decided a rebuild is needed. `doctor` also returns OK when offsets match (`doctor.rs:361-383`), whereas `diagnose` compares `cursor_hash` to `expected_last_hash` (`diagnose.rs:430-450`).\n\nImpact:\nRead commands that open the projection through `query::try_open_projection` can serve stale data when a shard is rewritten, conflict-resolved, restored from backup, or otherwise changed to a different valid log with the same byte length. The cursor hash is persisted specifically to identify the last replayed event, but the common auto-refresh path does not use it, so the projection can remain out of sync until an offset-changing write or explicit rebuild/diagnose exposes the mismatch.\n\nEvidence:\n- `db/query.rs:889-897` routes normal projection opens through `ensure_projection` when an events directory exists.\n- `db/mod.rs:83-92` reads both offset and hash but only uses the hash to detect a fresh zero-offset DB.\n- `incremental.rs:367-385` has a cursor hash validation helper, but it is not reached when byte lengths match.\n- `diagnose.rs:444-450` already models the expected last-hash comparison, proving the necessary signal is available.\n\nSuggested fix:\nTeach `ensure_projection` and `doctor` to compare `projection_meta.last_event_hash` against the current last parsed event hash when `last_event_offset` equals total log length. If the hash is missing or mismatched, trigger incremental/full rebuild or mark projection drift. Add coverage for a same-byte-length valid log rewrite where the final event hash changes but total content length remains unchanged.\n\nRelated:\nSearch showed older done work around projection drift (`bn-bae6b9c5c`, `bn-kfc4`), but this same-length/hash-mismatch case remains in the current code.","kind":"bug","labels":["fresh-eyes","projection","correctness"],"size":"m","title":"Projection auto-refresh misses same-length event log changes"}	blake3:UtzQ4vQEy4M4N-1qGFiHSexTrWsx6TzjVlhE8_7z4jw
