1777425148417289	bones-dev	itc:v3:AWKSZJkkk5JkmZMxAAAAQatWqrq1bWwAAAE3jA0		item.create	bn-1rjr	{"description":"Repro from /tmp/maw-bones-break-20260428-210908 using bones-cli 0.24.3 and maw 0.60.0.\\n\\nSteps:\\n1. Initialize a repo with git, maw, and bn init.\\n2. In ws/default, create and commit a bone, then run maw epoch sync.\\n3. Create a fresh maw workspace from main.\\n4. Confirm the new bone's item.create row exists in the fresh workspace's .bones/events/2026-04.events.\\n5. Before running any bn read command in that workspace, run bn update <id> --title ...\\n\\nObserved:\\nbn update fails with: item '<id>' not found, even though the event row is present. In the concrete repro, target bn-243 existed in ws/hank/.bones/events/2026-04.events, but bn update bn-243 failed. Running bn list --all first logged a full projection rebuild (fresh database/no cursor); the same bn update then succeeded and appended an item.update event.\\n\\nExpected:\\nMutating commands that resolve existing items should ensure the projection is initialized/rebuilt from present event shards before reporting item not found. A fresh workspace should not require users or agents to run bn list/show as a warmup before bn update/do/done/etc.\\n\\nWhy this matters:\\nIn maw workflows, fresh workspaces can contain current tracked .bones/events but no usable ignored .bones/bones.db projection yet. A false item-not-found can block agents or lead them to create duplicate bug/task bones.","kind":"bug","title":"Update commands miss existing items before initial projection rebuild"}	blake3:3jII8IkOQT2GoIQLPgpmFU6Q7Fc96a3pwMJsxucUaJY
1777425191185199	bones-dev	itc:v3:AWKSZJkkk5JkmZMxAAAAQatWqrq1bWwAAAE3jQ0		item.create	bn-12ki	{"description":"Repro from /tmp/maw-bones-break-20260428-210908 with bones-cli 0.24.3.\\n\\nSteps:\\n1. In a bones repo with events present, remove the ignored projection DB: rm -f .bones/bones.db.\\n2. Run: bn --format json list --all >stdout.txt 2>stderr.txt.\\n3. Parse stdout.txt as JSON.\\n\\nObserved:\\nstdout begins with projection rebuild log lines before the JSON object:\\nINFO falling back to full projection rebuild reason=\"projection database missing or corrupt\"\\nINFO projection rebuild complete ...\\n{ \"items\": ... }\\n\\npython3 -m json.tool stdout.txt fails with 'Expecting value: line 1 column 2'. stderr is empty.\\n\\nExpected:\\nWhen --format json is requested, stdout should contain only valid JSON. Diagnostic/projection rebuild logs should go to stderr, be suppressed unless verbose, or be represented in the JSON envelope.\\n\\nWhy this matters:\\nAgents and scripts reasonably pipe --format json into parsers. A normal first-run projection rebuild currently makes machine-readable output invalid.","kind":"bug","title":"Projection rebuild logs corrupt --format json stdout"}	blake3:8KNDksg-yGoxtYCa_rUSC8gTJPwNa3lhNzc50uX7w6I
1777425222619663	bones-dev	itc:v3:AWKSZJkkk5JkmZMxAAAAQatWqrq1bWwAAAE3jg0		item.update	bn-1rjr	{"field":"description","value":"Repro from /tmp/maw-bones-break-20260428-210908 using bones-cli 0.24.3 and maw 0.60.0.\n\nSteps:\n1. Initialize a repo with git, maw, and bn init.\n2. In ws/default, create and commit a bone, then run maw epoch sync.\n3. Create a fresh maw workspace from main.\n4. Confirm the new bone item.create row exists in the fresh workspace .bones/events/2026-04.events.\n\n5. Before running any bn read command in that workspace, run bn update <id> --title ...\nObserved:\nbn update fails with item not found, even though the event row is present. In the concrete repro, target bn-243 existed in ws/hank/.bones/events/2026-04.events, but bn update bn-243 failed. Running bn list --all first logged a full projection rebuild (fresh database/no cursor); the same bn update then succeeded and appended an item.update event.\n\nExpected:\nMutating commands that resolve existing items should ensure the projection is initialized/rebuilt from present event shards before reporting item not found. A fresh workspace should not require users or agents to run bn list/show as a warmup before bn update/do/done/etc.\n\nWhy this matters:\nIn maw workflows, fresh workspaces can contain current tracked .bones/events but no usable ignored .bones/bones.db projection yet. A false item-not-found can block agents or lead them to create duplicate bug/task bones."}	blake3:DcsFGGtzI2L55ssfld9XXZURvluWpA7jiyPrcn5LPgw
1777425222640277	bones-dev	itc:v3:AWKSZJkkk5JkmZMxAAAAQatWqrq1bWwAAAE3jw0		item.update	bn-12ki	{"field":"description","value":"Repro from /tmp/maw-bones-break-20260428-210908 with bones-cli 0.24.3.\n\nSteps:\n1. In a bones repo with events present, remove the ignored projection DB: rm -f .bones/bones.db.\n2. Run: bn --format json list --all >stdout.txt 2>stderr.txt.\n3. Parse stdout.txt as JSON.\n\nObserved:\nstdout begins with projection rebuild log lines before the JSON object:\nINFO falling back to full projection rebuild reason=\"projection database missing or corrupt\"\nINFO projection rebuild complete ...\n{ \"items\": ... }\n\npython3 -m json.tool stdout.txt fails with Expecting value: line 1 column 2. stderr is empty.\nExpected:\n\nWhen --format json is requested, stdout should contain only valid JSON. Diagnostic/projection rebuild logs should go to stderr, be suppressed unless verbose, or be represented in the JSON envelope.\nWhy this matters:\nAgents and scripts reasonably pipe --format json into parsers. A normal first-run projection rebuild currently makes machine-readable output invalid."}	blake3:tS4Vk8kcGtpRPi5di52HfM-wFogSAb_ITtx7GWuaGnI
